Incident.Summary: Initiated a traffic stop on a vehicle for speed. Driver arrested for DUI.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Subsequent offender: No

In-car camera mounted inside E-45 used for this stop.

  Rear- https://mdsp.evidence.com/axon/evidence?evidence_id=93b597222a624b2bba5a33fa48d2a6fe&partner_id=5ed6a168304e40eb9a0cfb1a226ef1a1

  Body- https://mdsp.evidence.com/axon/evidence?evidence_id=4e63ff67b2e44b8c91d187dd3e21f22c&partner_id=5ed6a168304e40eb9a0cfb1a226ef1a1

MD Driver's License: DE-1898901
Suspect: Ramirez-Chavez, Robin William
DUI #: 23-54-177
Phase One - Vehicle in Motion:
                On 08-19-2023 at 0243 hours I, TFC. Norfolk 7120 was patrolling the area of Rt.13 N/B @ Centre Rd, Salisbury MD 21801 when I observed a vehicle approaching me in the opposing S/B lanes. My calibrated moving radar mounted in E-45 captured a red Toyota Camry going 78 in a posted 45 MPH zone. I was able to call out to other Troopers a speed and direction in case someone else was closer. No one was closer to the subject than I was. I completed a U-turn at Centre Rd and started heading Southbound on Rt.13 where I was able to see the taillights of the vehicle. I was able to catch up to the vehicle and capture a second speed of 55 MPH in a posted 35 MPH zone. I initiated my emergency equipment and completed a traffic stop at Rt 13 S/B @ Naylor St, Salisbury MD. The weather was clear and warm; traffic was very light due to the time of night on a weekday.
Phase Two - Personal Contact:
               I approached the Toyota Camry from the driver's side of the vehicle and contacted Robin William Ramirez-Chavez 02-14-1999. I informed Ramirez-Chavez of the reason for the stop and advised him that everything was being audibly and visually recorded, I asked him to provide me with his license and registration. I was able to observe Ramirez-Chavez had a neon green wristband on his right wrist. I know through my training knowledge and experience that these styles of wristbands are used by bars so that the establishment knows the person is over 21 years of age. I also observed Ramirez-Chavez to have bloodshot and glassy eyes. Ramirez-Chavez was not the sole occupant inside the vehicle. Ramirez-Chavez had a female in the passenger seat that was intoxicated to the point she was falling asleep in the seat. While Ramirez-Chavez was providing me with his license and registration I was able to see that he had a slowed slurred speech along with slow reaction times when using his hands. I asked Ramirez-Chavez if he had anything to drink tonight, and he advised that he did have a beer earlier before driving. I asked Ramirez-Chavez to step out of the vehicle to complete the Standard Field Sobriety Testing, which he agreed.

Phase Three - Pre-Arrest Screening:
               Once Ramirez-Chavez was out of the vehicle I was able to smell a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from his breath and person. Ramirez-Chavez was asked again if he had anything to drink today when he advised that he did have a beer at Café Italiano. Ramirez-Chavez was observed to have trouble walking to the back of his vehicle and staggered from side to side while walking. Ramirez-Chavez also had difficulty standing upright without swaying from side to side.
                At the time of testing, Ramirez-Chavez was wearing tennis shoes. Ramirez-Chavez was also wearing appropriate clothing for the season, more specifically a loose shirt and jeans. The area where the testing was completed was flat and level and free from debris. The testing area was lit by my patrol vehicle's headlights and nearby streetlights.
               Before administering the tests, I asked Ramirez-Chavez if he had any medical conditions or physical issues that would keep him from completing any of the tests today which he advised that he had OCD. Ramirez-Chavez was asked if he wore contacts and or glasses, which he advised that he did not. My patrol vehicle's front-facing emergency equipment and spotlight were deactivated before beginning the tests.

The first test administered was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus Test:
 
 I explained the test to Ramirez-Chavez. He advised he understood my instructions and did not have any questions.
  • Displayed the lack of smooth pursuit and equal tracking in both eyes.
  • Displayed the Distinct and sustained Nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes.
  • Displayed the Onset of Nystagmus before 45 degrees in both eyes.
  • A check for Vertical Gaze Nystagmus was conducted with positive results.
If a subject has vertical nystagmus that clue indicates that their alcohol intake is at a maximum limit for that person.

A total of (six) clues were observed during this test.

The second test administered was the Walk and Turn Test:

I explained the test to Ramirez-Chavez. He advised he understood my instructions and did not have any questions.
  • Had to move feet from heel to toe contact and had to move his feet on multiple occasions to maintain balance
  • Stopped walking after step 3 on the first set of 9 steps and started to complete the turn.
  • Completed an improper turn by turning to the right while not using a series of steps.
  • Missed heel-to-toe on step 6 on the second set of steps during the test.
  • Stepped offline on steps 4,6 on the first set of steps and step 5 on the second set of steps during the test.
  • Took 8 steps on the first set of steps instead of the instructed nine steps.
A total of (6) clues were observed during this test.

The third test administered was the One Leg Stand Test:

I explained the test to Ramirez-Chavez. He advised he understood my instructions and did not have any questions.  
  • Put his foot down multiple times during the test in an attempt to keep from falling.
  • Swaying from side to side by approximately three inches during the test.
  • Raised arms approximately 18 to 20 inches from the side of his body to maintain balance at his count of 21 seconds.
  • Hopped during the test to try and maintain balance at his count of 22 seconds.
A total of two (4) clues were observed during this test.

                I offered Ramirez-Chavez the Preliminary Breath Test on the roadside using my calibrated PBT #14106 with a fresh straw that he watched me open from the plastic. Ramirez-Chavez agreed to take the PBT with a result of .19 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath.
                Based on observations of Ramirez-Chavez driving, physical appearance, and performance of SFST Ramirez-Chavez was placed under arrest for driving under the influence of alcohol at 0249 hours on 08-20-2023.
                Ramirez-Chavez was seated in my patrol vehicle. When I entered my vehicle, I could smell the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage that was not present before him being seated in it. Ramirez-Chavez was transported to the Salisbury Barrack for processing. While at the barrack, Ramirez-Chavez was read and allowed to read his DR-15 advice of rights. After completing the DR-15, Ramirez-Chavez refused the intoximeter at 0319 hours on 08-20-2023. Ramirez-Chavez Was provided with all copies of the paperwork and released from the Salisbury Barrack to a sober person on 08-20-2023 at approximately 0345 hours.  
                Ramirez-Chavez vehicle was not towed off scene, it was left in the parking lot that was located next to the traffic stop secured with the windows rolled up.
 
Based on all the above facts, I request that the case be closed by arrest.
CASE CLOSED.

All events occurred in Wicomico County, MD.
